Goal:
Introduce the two-workspace model: teacher workspaces for authoring and student workspaces for learning.

Context:
The project now needs to distinguish between:
- authoring/catalog workspaces
- learning/student workspaces

The agreed model is:
- teachers edit topics and learning items in teacher workspaces
- student workspaces are used for learning, assignments, and progress
- content is added/published from teacher workspace to student workspace
- assignments and active sessions must stay stable even if source content later changes

Feature:
Teacher Workspace + Student Workspace MVP

Scope:
1. Extend `workspaces.kind` to support:
   - `teacher`
   - `student`

2. Define permissions:
   - only `teacher` members may edit topics and learning_items
   - `student` members may learn, view their topics, and run sessions
   - do not add more roles in this slice

3. Introduce the minimal publish/add flow:
   - a teacher can add a topic or a set of learning items from a teacher workspace into a student workspace
   - keep the implementation minimal
   - do not build a broad publishing UI
   - do not build versioning

4. Student workspaces must not depend on fragile deletion behavior.
   Introduce content lifecycle rules:
   - no hard delete for used topics/learning_items
   - use archive/soft-delete flags where required

5. Enforce snapshot policy:
   - assignments store fixed item ids and title at creation time
   - active training sessions store fixed item ids at start time
   - later topic/content edits must not break old assignments or active sessions

6. Allow safe live edits where practical:
   - typo fixes
   - translation fixes
   - topic rename
   - topic membership changes for future launches

Cleanup rules:
- remove comments that still assume one flat workspace model if the new two-type model supersedes it
- remove dead code around old ownership assumptions if replaced cleanly
- do not keep stale TODO comments describing the old model as future direction
- if any handler/help text still lies about ownership or editing rules, update it

Out of scope:
- content versioning
- diff-based publishing
- synchronization back from student workspace to teacher workspace
- lesson model
- broad workspace management UI
- role expansion
- advanced deletion audit trail

Architecture constraints:
- Keep the implementation minimal
- Avoid building a full CMS
- Do not overengineer publish flow
- Prefer explicit, understandable code over abstract frameworks

Testing requirements:
- tests for workspace kind behavior
- tests that only teachers can edit content
- tests for add/publish behavior
- tests for snapshot assignment policy
- tests for soft-delete/archive behavior where introduced
- tests that active sessions remain stable after content changes
- focused tests without Telegram runtime where possible

Workflow:
1. architect
2. complexity_guard
3. coder
4. complexity_guard

Definition of done:
- teacher and student workspaces are modeled explicitly
- content editing is restricted to teacher members
- content can be added/published into student workspaces
- assignment and session snapshot rules are enforced
- soft-delete/archive policy exists for used entities where needed
- obsolete code/comments are cleaned up
- tests pass
- CHANGELOG.md and context/current_state.md are updated